column168: On May 24, 2007, a rolloff box was delivered to Veolia's 10-day in-transit yard located in Port Arthur, TX.  During the daily inspection on June 1, 2007, it was discovered that a spill of approximately one quart of liquid sludge material containing 8-300 PPM PCB material had leaked to the ground.  The area was remediated and the roll-off container was sent to Veolia's Port Arthur Incinerator for immediate disposal.      ***NOTE: This material was shipped using the Polychlorinated biphenyls, solid, UN3432 shipping description however, UN3432 is not an available option when completing this online form.
column169: Upon inspection it was determined that the leak was caused due to deterioration of an aging gasket on the rolloff container.  Veolia will notify the original transporter as well as the shipper of the problem and request they perform a more thorough inspection of the container prior to filling and shipping.

column168: A material handler was off-loading a semi trailer of waste at the Veolia facility in Menomonee Falls, WI. While off-loading a pallet, the forks of the liftruck extended beyond the pallet and punctured a 55 gallon steel closed head drum containing petroleum distillates. The material handler immediately notified his supervisor who was nearby. Together they tipped the drum onto its side, with the hole facing upward, to stop the leak. Then they placed the drum into an 85 gallon overpack and absorbed the spilled material with oil dry and properly disposed of the material.
column169: The incident was reviewed with the material handler including retraining on the proper operation of the lift truck and knowing where the forks are at all times.

column168: While traveling north on Santa Clara Ave in Oxnard Ca. other vehicle swerved into oncoming traffic lane. Carriers driver had to swerve to avoid hitting other vehicle head-on. The carriers tractors right front steer tire then left the pavement where there was no shoulder and a 10 foot drop off into a drainage ditch. Driver was unable to recorrect and keep the vehicle on the pavement. The carriers truck then went off the road, stuck a solid concrete embankment and came to a stop leaning at approximately a 45º angle into a drainage system. The Hazardous product that was being transported was violently shifted inside the van trailer causing 12 55gal. drums to rupture. Approximately 500 gallons product then escaped into the drainage system.    Carrier quickly mobilized environmental clean up teams local from the Oxnard area. Initial response was conducted by Black Gold Industries which immediately contained the release to keep it from spreading into the water system. They then pumped 8000 gallons of contaminated water into a recovery truck for disposal. Then ACTI was activated to perform major excavation to remove any residual material from the drainage system by removing the contaminated dirt and grass. After further review it was found that a high pressure natural gas line was present under ground and heavy equipment could not be used. ACTI then mobilized a large crew to manually dig up all contaminated soil. At this point Department of Fish and Game officers will be the final authorities and cleared the location. ACTI removed approximately 80 roll offs filled with contaminated soil and by products from the drainage system. 8000 gallons of contaminated water was pumped out of the drainage system and transported for disposal. As water run off continued to flow into the drainage system from unknown sources above the release area, it was pumped from a dammed up location to below the release area using a 150 gpm pump continuously during the clean up period.
column169: This road is very heavily traveled by both private vehicles and commercial vehicles transporting all types of commodities. The road surface should be widened at this location, either by increasing the shoulder area or by paving an area on the shoulder. It was noted that on the opposite side there is approximitly 75 feet of gravel pull off. So improving the traveled area is an appropriate remedy. In addition it was noted there is a agricultural road that is frequently used and vehicles traveling south commonly make right hand turns onto this road. Several each hour.    The driver of the vehicle may have stayed in his lane of travel but the final outcome may have been a far greater loss to both property and life. This would have caused an impact with an oncoming private auto head on.

column168: A BNSF train crew member reported GATX 18592 leaking product from its bottom outlet valve in the railyard. A receptacle was placed under GATX 18592 to catch leakage. A BNSF contract responder inspected GATX 18592 and found all valve seals intact. Seal numbered ITC 767339 was removed. The responder reported that the (TOBOV) top operated bottom outlet valve's operating rod was 1 1/2 turns open and the (BOC) bottom outlet cap was barely hand tight. The responder closed the TOBOV and tool tightened the BOC which ended any further product release by 1020 hrs. CDT, 6/01/07. The product captured in the receptacle was delivered to the consignee. All other ground impact spillage evaporated. Afterwards, GATX 18592 was released to proceed to the consignee's destination for unloading.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Union Pacific Railroad train YST65-18 delivered 31 cars to the CCT in track 5 at the Port yard in the Port of Stockton and when CCt performed the inbound interchange inspection the inspector found two tank cars Placarded UN1987 Ethanol that looked as if they had been leaking. Train Crew set the two cars to the repair track 808 and General Manager David Buccolo, who is a hazmat responder then inspected the cars and found that both cars, DBUX301252 and DBUX 301209 had indications of possible leaks from under the protective housing on top of the car. Seals from Midwest renewable energy were removed from the housing and housing was opened. The 2 inch induction fitting was observed to have to safety plug removed and the 2 inch ball valve was left in the open posistion allowing product to vent from the rail car. Car appears to have been venting while in transportation.  The 2 inch ball valve was closed and the safety plug was put in the fitting and secured with a 24 inch pipe wrench.
column169: Dave Buccolo General Manager has contacted the Union Pacific Railroad chemical transportation department and have contracted the Shipper, Midwest renewable energy to go over proper loading and securment procedures. this should insure all loading employees use proper procedures and checklists prior to releasing a shipment

column168: Portable anhydrous ammonia nurse tank was used to apply anhydrous ammonia fertilizer to Mr. Randy Magg's corn field.  Following the application, Mr. Magg parked the nurse tank in the field driveway.  Later that day, a passerby noted a cloud of anhydrous ammonia vapor around the product valves located on top of the nurse tamk.  The Superior, Iowa Volunteer Fire Department responded to the release, along with the Dickinson County Sheriff's Office.  280th. Ave. was closed for approximately one hour while the Fire Department controlled the release.  The Fire Department sprayed 100 gallons of water fog on the ammonia vapor cloud.  This allowed the Firemen to approach the nurse tank and tighten the leaking vale, ending the release.  The entire release occured as a vapor release to the atmosphere.  No injuries or evacuations were reported with this release and at no time did any of the anhydrous ammonia contact the waters of the State.  Officials investigating the release attribute the cause to a large change in internal tank pressure, coupled with a loose product valve on top of the tank.  Afternoon temperatures in the area approached 92*  Evening temperature fell to about 62* at the time of the release.  Officials speculate that the temperature change and resulting internal pressure change on the nurse tank's contents were the leading causes of the release.  Fire Department personnel were able to end the release by hand tightening the leaking product valve.  No cleanup efforts were required as the entire release occured as a vapor to the atmosphere.  The small amount of water used to fog the ammonia cloud soaked into the soil of Mr. Magg's corn field.
column169: Great Lakes Cooperative, the supplier of the anhydrous ammonia and the nurse tank, inspected the nurse tank following the release.  There was no damage found, or repairs needed, to the product valve.  Company employees will instruct all customers utilizing this equipment to make sure that all product valves are tight and secure before unhooking from the nurse tank.

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste was intransit between the point of origin and the intended waste management facility.  Upon arrival at the intended waste management facility, it was discovered that a container on the vehicle had leaked, allowing approximately 5 gallons of material to be released onto the floor of the van trailer.  Facility personnel immediately donned appropriate protective equipment and initiated appropriate response procedures.  Upon identification of the damaged container, it was determined that a 5 gallon polyethelene pail was placed between 2 larger containers.  During transportation, the load shifted and crushed the pail allowing the liquid to escape.  The response crew collected all spill material using a suitable absorbent material and disposed of it along with the damaged pail at the intended waste management facility.
column169: In order to prevent a recurrence, the driver will be re-instructed to insure that containers are loaded in such a way to preclude the potential for smaller containers to be crushed by larger, heavier objects.

column168: At approximately 12:00 pm on June 5, 2007 a minor release of hazardous waste onto a containment pad occurred from a sift-proof non-DOT Specification closed bulk bin (vacuum box).  At the time of the release, the bulk bin was being lowered onto the containment pad from the transport vehicle at a less than 10-day storage facility operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services (CHES) in Deer Park, TX.   While lowering the bin, the ratcheting mechanism used to tighten and hold the rear swing door secured, experienced a complete failure of material due to metal fatigue and corrosion and allowed the rear door to partially swing open.  Approximately 200 pounds of materials was released from the rear gate.  All of the released material was contained on a concrete pad.    Upon noticing the release, the driver swiftly lowered the bin onto the pad to allow the container to rest horizontally on the pad to minimize the quantity of the material released.  Thereafter, the driver stopped all operations, shut down his equipment, evacuated the area and notified his supervisor.  An in-house response crew was dispatched and arrived at the seen.  They retrieved and reviewed the shipping papers and determined that the material in the bulk bin was Waste toxic solids, corrosive, organic n.o.s. (hexachlorobutadiene, tetrachloroethylene) 6.1 (8) UN2928, PGII picked up earlier in the day at PPG Industries, Inc in Lake Charles, LA.      After reviewing the shipping papers, the response crew utilizing appropriate personal protection equipment and company health and safety policies and procedures entered the containment pad and commenced the clean up operations.  The rear door of the container was re-closed and secured by a chain and a come-along.  All of the released material was swept up and placed in to appropriate containers for future disposal at a permitted hazardous waste disposal facility.      The clean up operation was completed without any further incidents.
column169: The individuals involved with this shipment were informed of the equipment failure and were instructed to perform a more thorough equipment check prior to placing hazardous materials in transit.  Additional training for the drivers will be scheduled and proper bulk container closure and inspection procedures will be covered.
column172: Container, no description given (do not use if at all possible)

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: Driver started delivery of lead free gasoline. He went to check super lead free tank and found fill full of water and removed water from the fill. He proceeded to put the fitting on the fill, turned to the truck and opened the valve before hooking up the hose. The driver turned to see gas flowing on the ground. He shut down the flow, secured the area and called the local fire department and Farm & Home Oil and waited for response team, J & J Spill Company. This was an off-highway incident. There was no mechanical failure, just driver error.
column169: Proper unloading instructions were reviewed with the driver as follows:  Connect fitting and hoses to the tank first.  Connect vapor hose to trailer prior to delivery hose.  Do not initiate a gasoline delivery until all hoses are connected and secured.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: At approximately 12:30 pm on June 5, 2007 a minor release of hazardous waste onto a containment pad occurred from a sift-proof non-DOT Specification closed bulk bin.  At the time of the release, the bulk bin was being lowered from a transport vehicle onto a concrete storage pad at a less than 10-day storage facility operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services (CHES) in Deer Park, TX.   While lowering the bin approximately 20 gallons of sludge material splashed over the rear gate of the bulk bin.  All of the released material was contained on a concrete pad.    Upon noticing the release, the driver swiftly lowered the bin onto the pad to bring it to a horizontal position and minimize the release.  Thereafter driver stopped all operations, evacuated the area and notified his supervisor.  An in-house response crew was dispatched and arrived at the seen shortly thereafter.  They retrieved and reviewed the shipping papers and determined that the material in the bulk bin was Hazardous Waste Solid, n.o.s. (Centrifuge material contaminated with Benzene) 9, NA3077, PGIII picked up earlier that day at Premcor Refining Group, Inc in Port Arthur, TX.  Please note that at the time the material was loaded into the sift-proof bulk bin it was classified as being solid; however, it appears that during the course of transportation a small liquid layer formed on the top of the load due to vibrations and compression.   When the bulk bin was tilted to be off-loaded, the liquid layer spilled over the rear gate of the bin.    After reviewing the shipping papers, the response crew utilizing appropriate personal protection equipment and company health and safety policies and procedures entered the containment pad and commenced the clean up operations.  All of the released material was collected using appropriate absorbent materials and placed into appropriate containers for future disposal at a permitted hazardous waste disposal facility.  The cover of the bulk-bin was opened and the load was inspected for presence of any additional liquid.  It was determined that no more liquid remained in the container and it could be safely loaded onto the roll-on/roll-off vehicle for further transportation to the adjoining disposal facility.      The bulk bin was loaded and transported to the facility designated on the shipping papers without any further incidents.
column169: Our initial investigation concluded that the presence of liquid layer was either due to the waste material being pressed and settling during transportation and storage, or rainwater and condensate accumulating in the bulk bin.  The generator of this waste stream was contacted and informed of the incident.  They were also asked to address the preparation of this material for transportation and to ensure that no liquid material is added to this material prior to shipment.     The driver that originally picked up this container from the customer was reminded to conduct a thorough inspections of the containers at the time of the pick up to ensure that all closures are in place and that the intrusion by rainwater is prevented at all times.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: TILX 192658 was reported leaking product from the pressure relief device (PRD) atop this tank car while it was in the railyard. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder immediately inspected TILX 192658 and verified the product release was from the 75 psi PRD. The responder loosened the manway securement bolts to relieve internal pressure inside TILX 192658 and to check the product outage level.  Once the manway was opened, the PRD product release stopped. The product outage was less than two inches. All spillage evaporated.  The manway was resecured and TILX 192658 was carefully isolated in the railyard. The shipper was notified to make arrangements to off-load excess product in TILX 192658. On 6/13/07, excess product was transferred into a tanker truck without further incident. The product outage in TILX 192658 now measured 30 inches. A BNSF seal numbered 0024039 was applied and TILX 192658 was released to proceed to its destination.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings, including measures to ensure that proper product outages are adhered to.

column168: CSX Transportation received a call from Mr. Roger Spring with Marathon-Ashland in Catlettsburg, KY explaining that they were filling GATX 53917, Residue Xylenes, at their facility and discovered that it was leaking product from around the bottom outlet valve. They unloaded the product in the car and set the car out for repairs.  In the interval, CSXT's switch crew picked up the car in error and moved to our rail yard in Russell, Ky. Marathon-Ashland sent Rescar to the yard to inspect the car and found that it was "weeping" product from the flange adaptor on the bottom outlet cap. Rescar reported there was no actual liquid product drippage, just a wetness around the flange.  Rescar found that the nuts on the flange bolts were improperly torqued.  They re-torqued the nuts and the release stopped.  The car was then moved back to the Marathon-Ashland facility.    Cause Code:  662  NARRI:  2 (4+3+0) x (2+0) = 28
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On 06/09/07 at 09:00 hrs., the train crew reported an odor coming from tank car, GATX 71768, load Flammable Liquid, NOS. Trainmaster inspected car and found the manway cover bolts to be tight and no product visible on tank. Car was isolated and CSXT emergency response contractor, Eagle Construction and Environmental Services, Inc. (ECESI), was dispatched to the scene. ECESI personnel reported the packing gland nut for the top operated bottom outlet rod was loose, allowing release of vapor. ECESI personnel tightened the fitting and car was secured for release to final destination.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On June 14, 2007, at approximately 2050 hours, a railway tankcar GATX 6555, loaded with Sulfuric Acid, Spent, Corrosive, UN1832 PG II, was reported leaking at the Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) Beaumont, Texas yard. The tank car was discovered leaking from the manway cover. The shipper responded to the site and secured their container. Shipper handled decon and cleanup. There were no injuries, no damage to the environment.      Code: 200  Narri: 5(5+5+0)x(2+0)=100
column169: On The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR), shippers are immediately notified of all HAZMAT releases.  For non-accident releases (a.k.a. package or closure defects), where possible, shippers (responsible party) are requested to respond, repair and remediate.  By immediately involving the shipper, in-depth knowledge of the release cause is gained by the same organization that can implement process changes to prevent recurrence.  After each NAR incident, KCSR provides outreach to the shipper to help investigate root-cause factors for correction.  For non-accident related releases, the shipper should be contacted directly for details associated with actions taken to prevent recurrence.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  Upon opening the trailer door at the Roadrunner Dawes Freight Systems, Inc. facility, a leak was discovered.  Area was isolated and secured, pending arrival of outside contractor assistance.  NRC Environmental Services of Long Beach, California was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Upon inspection of the trailer, NRC Environmental Services determined that one 5-gallon poly drum was punctured by a nail inside the trailer.  Approximately 5 gallons of corrosive liquid, nos were released inside the trailer.  NRC Environmental Services applied absorbent material to the free liquid, which was containerized, along with the damaged drum, into two (2) 55-gallon recovery drums, pending disposal.  NRC Environmental Services proceeded to pressure wash the trailer floor, to remove any residual product, and containerized the wash water into one (1) 55-gallon drum.  Three (3) 55-gallon drums were transported by NRC Environmental Services to Crosby & Overton for disposal.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and appears to be related to a nail puncture during transit, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  Roadrunner Dawes Freight Systems, Inc. will continue to reinforce safe handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: On Monday, June 11th at 1803 hours Hamlet Yard Car Foreman reported Tank Car ARIX 1246 (Load - Carbon Dioxide, Refrigerated Liquid) venting vapors and observed ice around the protective housing cover.  CSX Transportation Terminal Manager arranged to isolated the railcar and implimented the corportation's emergency response plan.  Chemtrec was contacted (Report Number 2007061100177) and the shipper, BOC Gases was notified of the release.  Hepaco Environmental was contracted by CSX to respond and inspect the railcar.  Hepaco representatives found the container leaking vapors and liquid between the manway nozzle and pressure plate assembly.  The pressure plate securement bolts / nuts were inspected and found to be tool tight.  Arrangements were made with BOC Gases to responded with a crew and MC331 trucks to transfer the product.  On Tuesday, June 12th at 1700 hours BOC Gases completed the transfer of contents.  Approximately 20 gallons of liquid was released from the tank car prior to the completion of the transfer.  BOC Gases will  apply for an FRA Movement Approval to forward the tank car to a qualified facility for repairs.     Cause Code: 220  NARRI:  5(5+1+0) x (3+0) = 90

column168: SHPX 202413 in train Q38613 was found by a car inspector to have product dripping down the side of the tank car, evaporating prior to reaching the ground. CSX initiated their Transportation Emergency Response Plan and notified the local Fire Department. Trainmaster Payne investigated and noticed product dripping from the valve housing. The Selkirk Fire Department ordered the yard closed, evacuated all employees to the car and locomotive shops. FD deneid entry to the scene by CSXT ER contractor, Miller Environmental. All personnel where held out of the site until 2110 hours when the Albany HazMat Team made entry and discovered the leak had stopped. Miller Environmental was then allow to inspect the car and  found the liquid line valve was less than tool tight and was not fully seated on the liquid line eduction nipple. The the valve body asymbly was secure by tightening 1.5 turns. The tank car was then staged for 24 hours to verify that there was no further leakage.  The shipped secured from the FRA, a Movement Approval before the car was sent forward to destination.    Cause Code:  282  NARRI:  5 (5+3+0) x (2+4) = 240

column168: According to the information obtained the following occurred.  While at the TA Truck-stop in Ogallala, Nebraska, free product was discovered leaking from the trailer.  RMCAT Environmental Services, Inc. of Denver, Colorado was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  RMCAT Environmental Services, Inc. applied absorbent material to contain the free liquid on the impacted asphalt surface.  RMCAT Environmental Services, Inc. investigated the trailer and discovered one, leaking 55-gallon drum.  Approximately 10 gallons of free product were released.  The leak was due to a faulty gasket on a bung.  RMCAT Environmental Services, Inc. applied additional absorbent material as needed to recover the free liquid inside of the trailer.  The leaking drum was placed into an 85-gallon over pack drum.  One, 85-gallon overpack drum containing the leaking drum and one, 55-gallon drum of contaminated absorbent material were generated as a result of the incident.  No injuries or exposures were reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and may have been related to a faulty gasket, no actions have been taken to prevent recurrence.  However, Roadrunner Dawes Freight Systems, Inc. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: BN 974392 was reported leaking product from its top fittings while in the railyard. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspected BN 974392 finding product leaking at the blind flange to the liquid line valve. The responder reduced internal pressure inside BN 974392 by opening the secured manway cover. Once internal pressure was relieved, the product leak was stopped by 2305 hrs. PDT, 6/03/07. BN 974392 was resecured and carefully moved to the BNSF fuel unloading rack in the Spokane railyard. BN 974392 was fully unloaded without further incident. A BNSF environmental contractor was called and remediated all ground impact spillage. The side specification stencil on BN 974392 indicated that the tank qualification was completed in 2002 and due in 2012. Since the ambient high temperatures were in the 90 degree F range for the last week, it appeared that the combination of product expansion, rising internal pressure and possibly the incorrect product outage for these temperatures lead to the product release at the flanged closure. BN 974392 was earmarked for additional mechanical inspection of the flange and flange gasket by a qualified repair facility prior to future reloading.

column168: ON JUNE, 2007 OUR INDEPENDENT CONTRACTOR DRIVER WAS TRAVELING FROM PONCE ( SOUTH) TO QUEBRADILLAS (NORTH WEST) HAULING 10,000 GALLONS OF GASOLINE.  THE DRIVER WAS TRAVELING ON ROAD #10 IN ADJUNTAS, WHEN THE DRIVER GET TO  THE INTERSECTION 55/G ON ROAD #10. HE APPLIES THE BRAKES OF THE TRUCK TRACTOR BUT THE BRAKES DO NOT RESPOND.  IMMEDIATLEY THE DRIVER APPLY THE EMERGENCY BRAKES OUT THE THE BRAKES DO NOT RESPOND.  WHEN THE DRIVER GET INTO THE CURVE THE TRUCK TRACTOR AND THE CARGO TANK OVERTURN ON ROAD #10.  THIS OVERTURN PROVOKE A SPILL OF GASOLINE APPROXIMATELY 1,050 GALLONS THAT GET ON THE GROUND.  1
column169: WE SUSPEND THE CONTRACT WITH THE DRIVER, BECAUSE WE BELIEVE THAT THE REAL CAUSE OF TIS ACCIDENT WAS THE SPEED.  AT THE SAME TIME WE DESIGN A PROCEDURE WHERE WE ESTABLISH THE PROHIBITION TO OUR DRIVER TO TRAVELING FOR ROAD #10 IN ADJUNTAS.  WE UNDERSTAND THAT THE ROAD #10 IN ADJUNTAS IT IS A DANGEROUS ROAD.

This ATV was manufactured and shipped from a foreign location.  Since there is no UN3166 entry under the IMDG, the shipper moved the ATV with the battery acid pack under the UN2796 Battery Fluid Acid description and marked the package appropriately.  The current shipper then reshipped the same item from a domestic location to another domestic location.  Normally, this would move as non hazardous since it is a new piece of equipment but the battery acid is not in the battery but rather is separately packaged to avoid the battery activation.  The current shipper should have shipped this as it was shipped to him but he did not.  The error was discovered during a TAG inspection for tariff compliance.
column169: All packages should be checked for marking and labeling and compared with the shipping document to ensure compliance.  I suspect that the person completing the bills and the person loading the container never discussed the possible hazardous nature of this ATV.

column168: On Sunday, June 17th at 1414 hours RailLink (Local Shortline Railroad) reported tank car UTLX12636 (Load - Sulfuric Acid) releasing product from top of car while being switched within the interchange yard in Oglethorpe, GA.  RailLink representatives contacted the consignee, Weyerhaeuser Corporation and informed the industry of the release.  Weyerhaeuser placed a call to Chemtrec (Report Number 2007061700029) and the shipper, Tronox, LLC was notified of the incident.  CSX Transportation contacted SWS Environmental to respond and secure the container as we were the last railroad to handle the car prior to the release.  Once on site, SWS representatives found the cause of the release to be four of four fill hole securement bolts / nuts being less than tool tight.  The bolts / nuts were properly tightened and the car was released to destination.  Approximately ten (10) gallons of sulfuric acid was released from railcar.    NARRI: 5(5+5+0)*(2+0)=100  Cause Code = 224

column168: A BNSF train was stopped in emergency on the main track at Sprague, WA and the BNSF crew reported that the B-end coupler on intermodal flatcar BNSF 231120 fell off. Further inspection by the train crew revealed that the coupler knuckle cart-wheeled under this flatcar striking the floor of intermodal container HDMU 228184 and then lodged under the flatcar. A small amount of product powder, estimated at one cup, was found on the platform of the intermodal flatcar under HDMU 228184, which contained 80 drums of imported (from China) powdered Vanadium Pentoxide. BNSF contract responders inspected HDMU 228184 finding a hole in the container floor (2 feet long by 1 foot wide). A 55 gallon steel drum directly above this floor hole had a 6-8 inch dent on the drum bottom, but no drum compromise could be seen. The contractor cleaned the small amount of spillage on the flatcar platform and wiped the coupler knuckle that was recovered. After the coupler knuckle was replaced, the train proceeded to Spokane, where the flatcar BNSF 231120 with the damaged container (HDMU 228184) was setout. HDMU 228184 was deramped for a complete interior inspection. On 6/19/07, the same response contractors unloaded the drums from HDMU 228184. During the drum unloading, several drums were noted with loose top drum lid retainer ring bolts and these were tightened with no product spillage incurred. Responders also found two 55 gallon drums (UN 1A2/X2/50S/07) that had been dented from the knuckle impact. One of these drums had a dime sized hole at the drum bottom in the dented area. When this drum was lifted, no product leaked out, but there was product on the container floor near this drum; and it was cleaned. The two dented drums were placed into 85 gallon overpack drums and properly labeled. All lading from HDMU 228184 was transferred into another intermodal container without further incident and forwarded to the consignee.

column58: Cylinder Valve; Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Non-Reclosing
column168: At approximately 0437 hours, 6-5-07, Javier Ybanez, Branch Logistics Manager at the Apria Healthcare facility located at 610 S. Douglas St., El Segundo, CA. arrived at the branch. He heard a noise coming from the rear of the building and upon investigation he observed a cloud in the area of the 6500 gallon stand tank containing Oxygen, refrigerated liquid. Upon unlocking and opening the gate he observed that the sound and vapor cloud was coming from a pressure release valve. At that time there was a large accumulation of ice around the valve and a small amount on the concrete under the tank. There was no liquid present.    Upon securing safety equipment he went to the valve and was able to force it shut.  He then called the Warehouse Supervisor advising him to respond to the branch. While waiting he secured the perimeter around the stand tank.    It was determined that on 6-4-07 they had received a delivery of Oxygen, refrigerated liquid from Air Gas, Vernon, CA. At that time the tank had been filled. Examination found that approximately 31” or 527 gallons had been released.    A technician from Cryotech, VBS International, Anaheim, CA responded to their request to inspect and repair the tank. The technician found that both burst discs and the pressure release valve had failed. The necessary repairs were completed. The technician advised that it was probable that when the delivery was made it was conducted at high pressure and that was the cause of the failures.    Air Gas was notified of the incident.
column169: Air Gas has been requested to remind their drivers that the pressure during fills must be made at the proper pressure. This is a low pressure tank and filling it at an excessive pressure will damage the tank and creates a hazardous condition.    Apria staff have been instructed that if a fill is conducted during business hours that they are to verify the fill pressure being utilized. Following every fill, attended or unattended, an inspection of the tank will be conducted to check for damage.

column168: On 6/21/07, a 55 gallon open top metal drum containing a mixture of solvents was identified as leaking while at the Veolia Huntington Beach 10 day in-transit location.   A small leak was noticed through the trailer in which this material was loaded and was awaiting further transportation to its final destination.  Immediately upon discovery action was taken to mitigate the release by using oilsorb material to prevent the spread of the release. The container had leaked approximately less than 1 gallon of liquid on the trailer floor. A pinhole leak was observed on the outer body of this metal drum.  The drum was carefully placed on its side with the pinhole facing up and was packed into a "SALVAGE" container, an 85 gallon poly overpack.  The spilled material on the floor of the trailer was cleaned up using oilsorb, rags and was decontaminated as well.
column169: This leak was the result of combining various solvents that are believed to hold corrosive properities which contributed to the container failure.  It is very important to ensure appropriate containers are used for the chemicals being packaged even though this was an authorized container under the DOT packaging standards for the hazard class and the proper shipping name.  In the future, corrosion tests of the liquid being poured into the drum must be done before combining various solvents.

column168: Passenger/Customer was in terminal gate area using his laptop plugged into 110V outlet.  The laptop began to smoke and agents asked him to unplug it from wall outlet.  He refused.  Shortly after, the laptop became too hot for the customer to handle.  Video of incident may indicate he was succesful in removing the battery pack from the laptop.  Shortly thereafter it began exploding Li-ion cells one at a time in a thermal runaway and catching fire.    Airport Fire/Rescue personnel responded with fire extinguisher(s) directed at the fire/battery pack.  A lot of smoke/vapor from the fire/fire extinguishers was generated.  Passengers cleared the immediate area of the gate where the fire occured but the building is a "satellite" type of layout with a common area containing about 6-8 gates.  The entire area was not evacuated as it is a large seating area.  Passengers waiting to board the flight simply moved away from the immediate area.    Discussions with Dell Computer revealed that the battery pack may have been one that was recalled last year.  Unfortunately, the remains of the battery pack were disposed of by the LAX Airport Fire Department and we were unable to obtain them prior to final disposal.    An airport Police report was filed on the occurance.  The passenger boarded the flight with his laptop but without the battery pack.
column169: American Airlines has developed a procedure to alert the appropriate individuals whenever a thermal runaway of a battery occurs including gathering of information and evidence to report to Federal Agencies.    More public awareness is required to inform the consumer that keeping a battery plugged in to an outlet while using the computer may not be safe.  Recommendations should made to either use the laptop without the battery or the laptop with the battery but not plugged in to a power outlet of any type.

A straight truck containing non-bulk packages of hazardous waste was enroute between the shipper's location and the intended waste management facility noted on the shipping paper.  During the course of transportation, the shipment was stored in-transit for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities into a van trailer for continuing transportation.  Upon arrival at Clean Harbors in-transit facility located at 211 Holiday Avenue in Cannon Falls, MN; facility personnel detected a solvent odor coming from the rear door of the straight box truck.  Facility personnel donned appropriate personal protective equipment and entered the trailer.  It was determined that a pinhole leak had developed in the side wall of one of the 55 gallon closed head steel drums containing waste paint.  It is estimated that approximately 16 ounces of material had escaped to the floor of the trailer and approximately 2-3 ounces escaped onto the asphalt parking area.  Facility personnel placed the damaged container into a suitable salvage drum and cleaned up all released material using a suitable absorbent material.  This material was placed into the 85 gallon salvage drum and was sent for disposal to the fully licensed waste management facility identified on the shipping paper.
column169: At the time of loading, the containers were inspected and no evidence of leaking was detected.  In order to prevent a recurrence, the driver has been reinstructed to insure that he continues to conduct a container by container inspection during loading and any damaged and/or questionable drums be addressed before accepting for transportation.

column168: A BNSF switch crew reported a light chlorine smell emanating from PROX 89497 (DOT 105J500W) in the railyard. PROX 89497 was immediately cordoned off in the railyard, but later after the chlorine odor subsided, it was moved and isolated in the railyard. BNSF contract responders inspected PROX 89497 and reported finding two loose mounting flange stud nuts at the base of the B-end liquid line valve. Responders tool tightened these loose flange nuts four complete turns each which ended any further chlorine vapor release. Responders also checked all the other valves and found at least two loose flange stud nuts on the other valves, which were also tool tightened. Securement was completed by 0230 hrs. CDT, 6/06/07 and PROX 89497 was released to proceed to its destination.   At approximately 0630 hrs. CDT on 6/12/07 at the BNSF Alliance (Haslet, TX) railyard, a BNSF switch crew reported a chlorine odor emanating from PROX 89497. PROX 89497 was cordoned off. A BNSF contract responder inspected PROX 89497 finding a small leak at the B-end liquid valve flange above the pressure plate. The mounting flange stud nuts were tool tight. The contractor applied and secured a chlorine capping kit which ended the product odor by 1010 hrs. CDT, 6/12/07. PROX 89497 continued to be monitored by this Chlorep approved contractor. Movement approval FRA-07060175 was obtained to move PROX 89497 to a closer consignee location in Cleburne, TX for unloading. PROX 89497 arrived at the consignee location at Cleburne without further incident.   Suspect that the mounting flange gasket was either cut or pinched under the B-end liquid valve flange.

column168: On June, 27 2007, our truck was driving down I-35 hedding into Harlingen Texas.  As he was driving the driver noticed an ammonia leak coming out the back of his truck.  The driver immediately pulled his truck to the side of the road to investigate the leak.  When the driver got to the back of his trailer he noticed that the 1" hose came loose and was rubbing on the ground.  A hole was rubbed into the hose allowing the ammonia in the hose to leak out.  The duration of this leak was about two minuets. The hose was iolated from the main tank by a block vlave, so only the product in the hose was released.  It is very hard to determine how much liquid ammonia was in the hose because most of the liquid is removed at the time of delivery.  It is a strong posiability that there was only vapor in the hose at the time of the leak.  The locking nut on the hose real apparently loosened allowing the hose to fall to the ground.  A new hose real will be installed.
column169: Because of the block valves between the tank and the hose, this release was minimized.  A new hose real will be installed and the locking nut will be inspected daily.  The hose will also be replced.

column168: The box came open during the sort. We found several bottles of perfume. I called the shipper to inquire about the shipment. I advised him that Express Saver is not a ground service. FedEx Express does not offer ground service, only FedEx Ground does that. At no time during the conversation did Abraham mention DOT-SP 9275. Abraham did say that when he offers his perfume to an international destination, he’ll place a class 9 label on the box per instructions from UPS. I advised that this shipment wasn’t offered properly for a ground shipment. The FAA was notified, I spoke to SA Kathy Hug, DTW FAA. The freight was held pending an FAA inspection.

column168: Univar driver arrived at customer location to make a delivery.  Upon arriving and entering the trailer, the driver noticed a small puddle of the Carusol had leaked onto the floor of the trailer.  The driver moved the IBC away from the wall to identify the source of the leak and discovered the buckle on the load securement device had rubbed a small pinhole in the plastic sidewall of the IBC.  The driver immediately notified the customer, then contacted his dispatch supervisor to report the problem.  The dispatch supervisor notified the operations manager and a group of three trained individuals were sent to the customer location.  The remaining material in the IBC was transfered to another empty IBC of the same product and the spilled material was cleaned up and disposed of in accordance with all required regulations.  A total of .5 gallons was spilled, only a small amount (one cup) spilled onto the customers asphalt, the rest spilled onto the floor of the trailer.
column169: An incident investigation was conducted to determine the root cause of the failure.  All individuals within this department have been briefed on this incident and trained how to properly secure IBC's of this nature in the future.  Also, this incident will be reviewed by the facility's Safety Committee.

column168: Rail Car was loading Dichloropropene from a shore tank.  The loading was required to be "closed" system.  A meter was being used for loading quantities.  The transfer orders requested that the tank be stripped to this railcar. When the meter stop was reached, the operator started the transfer back up and loaded more into the car, mistakenly thinking there was room in the car for all the chemical in the tank.  The operator did not use a redundant means of overfill protection, (required for all "closed system" loads).  THe car overfilled and 600 gallons for Dichloropropene was released into a contained area.  Water spray was used to suppress vapors and the chemical was washed to a closed wastewater system.  The duration of the actual release was about 5 minutes, adn all material was washed into a closed system adn vapor suppressed in 30 minutes after release.  Actual release to the environment consisted only of material that vaporized to the atmosphere, adn was calculated to be ~77 pounds.
column169: Retraining for the two operators involved in this event.  A meter stop was ignored adn procedure requires a secondary method of overfill protection for all "closed System" loads.  The secondary protection, in this case an electronic probe was not used.  All operators are communicated with on the importance of redundant overfill protection.  This event was de-briefed with all operators and consequences reviewed adn understood.

column168: At approximately 1730 CST on June 14, 2007 an MC 307 tanker truck transported by Clean Harbors Environmental Services (CHI) was involved in a motor vehicle accident at the intersections of routes 23 and 24 in Hoxie, KS.  As a result of the collision with a passenger automobile, the truck and the trailer rolled over onto a graveled section of a parking lot of an adjoining business northbound on highway 23.  At the time of the collision, the truck was transporting approximately 4,100 gallons of Hazardous Waste Liquid n.o.s. (Benzene) 9 NA3082 PGIII material.  As a result of the roll over, the pipes connecting the scrubber assembly on the tanker truck were fractured and began slowly seeping liquid materials onto the roadway and the graveled section of the parking lot.  Hoxie fire department, ambulance, and police were on the scene of the accident within minutes.  The fire department deployed spill containment equipment to prevent the waste material from entering any waterways or contaminating larger area.  Both the driver of Clean Harbor’s vehicle and the driver of the passenger vehicle were transported to the Sheridan County Hospital by ambulance and later transferred by air to Wesley Medical Center in Wichita, KS.  Clean Harbors driver was treated for non-life threatening injuries and released after 3 days, the condition of the other driver is unknown at this time due to patient confidentiality laws.  Due to Clean Harbor’s driver’s injuries, Clean Harbors was notified of the event by Sheridan County Sheriff’s Department at 1910 EST.  Clean Harbors immediately dispatched a subcontracted emergency response provider in the area to respond to the scene.  Because of the approximately 2 hour mobilization time required for the ER provider to arrive on the scene, Sheridan County Emergency Management coordinator decided to transfer the material from the leaking tanker into a compatible tanker to avoid any catastrophic release.  The material was transferred and Clean Harbors truck and trailer up-righted without any incidents.  The duration of the release was approximately 4 hours from the time of the roll-over, until the material was transferred and the vehicles up-righted.  Concurrently, Clean Harbors dispatched an empty tanker truck to the scene to remove the waste material from the tanker truck used by the Sheridan County emergency management agency.  The waste material was transferred into the tanker dispatched by Clean Harbors, and the material transported to the waste disposal facility without any further issues.  The emergency response company contracted by Clean Harbors commenced remediation activities at the site of the accident.  All spill containment material, the contaminated gravel and soil was removed and placed into appropriate containers for future disposal at permitted hazardous waste facility. Upon completion of the remediation, soil samples were collected from the site and analyzed to ensure that no contamination was present.  Upon satisf
column169: Clean Harbors is continuing investigating this accident and working with the driver, the witnesses and the Hoxie, KS police department.  Upon finalization of the management team investigation, the appropriate actions will be taken to prevent recurrences of such an event.

column168: The driver connected a two inch hose from the tanker to the customer’s bulk tank line.   After everything was checked the driver asked the customer was he ready for him to pump product from the tanker.  The customer told the driver that everything was ready and to start pumping.  The driver opened the tanker valves and the valve on the customer's line at the point where the hose was connected.  The driver started the truck pump.  Immediately after engaging the truck pump the hose separated from the banded female camlock fitting.  The driver immediately stopped the pump.  All valves were closed immediately.  No personnel reported any product splashed on them.  Product was confined in the customer's containment.  The customer cleaned up the spill material.  The customer found the secondary valve on their bulk line had still been closed.  The driver used another hose to reconnect the tanker to the customer's bulk line.  The customer made sure that all valves on their line were open.  The driver opened the valves on the tanker and pumped the load without any further incident.  Hose test certification was reviewed.  Hose inspections were reviewed.  No negative information was noted.  All hoses were annually tested and passed at 225 PSI 01/08/2007.  The hose and fitting was inspected by the Branch Operations Supervisor, Tank Farm Leadman, and hose supplier representative.  It was noted that the two banding clamps on the outside of the hose were positioned directly above the two raised grip ridges on back bonding section of the camlock fitting.  This would allow the fitting the possibility of slipping out the hose.  Investigation determined cause as hose coupling failure.
column169: Hoses were inspected for band positions.  Supplier initiated internal review of bonding process and performed an additional inspection of hoses.  Hose coupling devices have been converted to supplier’s recommendation of machine pressed stainless steel sleeves to maximize bonding of hose and coupling devices.

A BNSF train taking siding on single main track derailed eight hazardous material ladened tank cars upright while entering the siding. The cause of this derailment was attributed to a gapped switch point at the siding switch. One of these derailed tank cars, TILX 190946 (DOT 111A100W1), derailed leaning and collided with the lead locomotive on a BNSF train stopped on the main track at the clearance point. This side collision sheared-off the liquid and vapor valves atop TILX 190946, as well as, damaging (crushing) the pressure relief device (PRD). Product from TILX 190946 escaped from the valve orifices and the PRD. The valve orifices were plugged which stopped the product release. Product drips continued from the damaged PRD until TILX 190946 was uprighted. Ground spillage was remediated. The remaining product in TILX 190946 was transferred into tanker trucks on 7/11/07 without further incident.

column168: Driver was transferring lading from cargo tank to consignee's storage tank by means of a cargo hose connection to storage tank's receiving line.  Air pressure was applied to cargo tank in order to accomplish transfer.  With the liquid transfer complete, driver isolated air pressure delivery to cargo tank and continued to allow cargo tank to vent-down thereby relieving air pressure in cargo tank.  Driver thought air pressure was relieved and began disconnect of cargo hose connection.  Residual pressure remained in cargo tank and began venting air and acid mist from end of disconnected cargo hose.  Duration of release was approximately five minutes.  Driver shutdown cargo tank internal valve to stop release.
column169: Cause of the incident was a failure to follow written unloading procedures.  Driver was required to shutdown internal and external valves on cargo tank then close valve on consignee's storage tank for disconnecting cargo hose.  Driver was removed from service and assigned to a driver trainer for further training and evaluation.

column168: Investigation shows that during the truck to rail transfer of 90% Spent Sulfuric Acid a miscalculation was made causing to railcar to be overfilled. Acid ran up the 1-inch vapor srubber line and down into the scrubber tank. The sulfuric acid blended with the scrubber (hydrogen peroxide and water) solution in the scrubber tank. This created a violent reaction. Once this happened the loader shut down the rack immediately upon seeing steam boiling from the scrubber unit.  The plastic srubber tank melted from the heat of the chemical reaction and approximately 150 gallons of a diluted spent sulfuric acide mixture spilled onto the ground. Daming and diking was implemented to prevent acid from migrating off-site. Soda Ash was used to neutralize the diluted solution on the ground. CURA was notified and a HAZMAT response team was dispatched. The HAZMAT team arrived within the hour to begin cleaning and disposing of the contaminated material.
column169: 1) All customer service reps were retrained on checking the inventory sheet against the computer system before a sulfuric acid load is sent to a railcar.    2) Verifying employee must physically watch the loader open the dome lid of railcar to confirm there is adequate room in the railcar for product before loading.    3)High Level alarms will be used on all sulfuric acid railcars to alert loader if the railcar is being overloaded.    4) Develop specific work instructions for loading spent sulfuric acid in Philadelphia.

column168: While in transport, one of the tires of the tractor-trailer caught fire, causing the the trailer and its contents to also catch fire.  The local fire department was dispatched to the scene and extingueished the fire.  The trailer caught on fire again and the local fire department put this fire out.  The fire caused the containers inside the trailer to melt, and some of the containers fell out of the onto soil after the walls of the trailer burned.  After the fire was extinguished, the containers that were on soil and some of the soil that was impacted were placed in rolloff boxes.  The remainder of the cargo melted into a fused mass of plastic and adhesive.  Samples were taken and analyzed to determine proper disposal procedures.  The rolloff boxes were transported to the appropriate disposal facility and disposed of.  The trailer was taken to the towing company's storage facility and was later disposed of at a metal recycling facility.  The site was covered with polyethylene sheeting and secured.  The area was excavated at a later date and all contaminated soil was removed and properly disposed of.  Closure samples were taken and analyzed, the site was backfilled, graded, restored, and cleanup was completed.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: While in transit, product was spotted leaking from the trailer. The fire department at the scene found the drum leaking from a hole caused by a nail that was sticking up from the shipper's pallet. The fire department overpacked the drum for safe transit and cleaned up the spilled product.
column169: The carrier notified the shipper of the issue.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: Upon off-loading the trailer, 1 drum from Sunoco was discovered to be leaking. Further inspection revealed that the cause was a package failure via a spilt seam on the drum. The small spill was cleaned up and the container overpacked and held pending further disposition.
column169: Jevic to discuss with the shipper the suspected package failure.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: While unloading a wooden pallet with the subject plastic non-bulk drum containing UN 3109, the lower side of the drum caught on a sharp object (the edge of an adjacent pallet?) or other and was punctured. Approximately 1 quart of product was spill on the warehouse floor. No human contact or exposure was reported; however, there were two employees in the near vicinity.     The drum was immediately turned on its side to prevent further leakage. Shortly thereafter, a portable containment tray was taken to the area and the damaged drum placed within. A environmental response contractor was called out to the facility (i.e. Cliff Berry Interantional) for remediation. The cleanup was completed within a couple of hours, as the damaged drum was placed within a salvage drum for further transportation. END OF REPORT
column169: It appears as if this type of packaging i.e. plastic non-bulk drums, are a not strong enough to withstand accidental contact with, for example, corners of pallets or other packages, protruding nails from pallets, etc.     It is recommended that these types of packages be re-evaluated for hazmat transportation purposes.    END OF REPORT

column169: CYLINDERS, AND OTHER LARGE PACKAGING CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS OR CHEMICALS MUST B SAFELY HANDLED AND MOVED USING THE APPROPRIATE AND SAFE EQUIPTMENT KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS AND ALLOW ENOUGH SPACE FOR MOVEMENT TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED AND AREA IS SAFE FOR WORKING. column168: Driver departed shipper location and proceeded west on I-10 to I-8 westbound.  At first exit after transition driver exited freeway and performed inspection of equipment.  Driver noticed lading leaking from cargo tank at rear sump.  Driver made a dike from soil in the area to contain spread and made notifications.  Police and fire responded to secure area.  Company sent another cargo tank to location and transferred lading.  Leaking cargo tank was decontaminated and towed to repair facility.  Lading leaked from cargo tank at a rate of 0.2 gallons per minute for approximately four hours.  Environmental cleanup contractor was engaged to decontaminate equipment and remove impacted soil.
column169: HM inspection of cargo tank lining was completed five months prior to failure.  No defects were found at that time.  It is recommended that conductivity tests be performed after loading cargo tank to ensure lining integrity prior to releasing vehicle from shipping location.

Driver was pumping product from cargo tank to customers storage tank that was 350 feet away and 30 feet up.  When the storage tank was nearing the fill line, the driver closed the valve on the cargo tank and opened it 1/4 turn to slow the flow of the product.  It wasn't enough, however, to move the product into the tank.  When he opened it a little more, product came out of the vent on the top of the tank.  Spill was hosed to the customer containment drainage system.
column169: The lenght of the fill line made it difficult to adjust the flow of the product near the end of the unload.  Putting less product in the tank would have prevented the overflow.

column168: One can of hazmat/DGR found during a security check of an air export shipment described as " personal effects" not restricted. The forwarder would ensure that personal effects shipments are pysically checked every time. The shipper has advised their staff to not include any hazmat/DGR items in air cargo shipments.   The can of flammable aerosol was removed from the shipment and the shipment was releared by the FAA , then transported to destination.

column42: ENGINES INTERNAL COMBUSTION, OR ENGINES, FUEL CELL, FLAMMABLE LIQUID POWERED
column168: Container HRZU431340-4 was tendered to the ocean carrier Horizon Lines for shipment from Tacoma, Washington to Dutch Harbor, Alaska.  A routine TAG (The Adnerence Group) tariff compliance inspection revealed that the container had a liquefied petroleum gas (propane) powered forklift with a full tank of propane on it.  The customer was notified that the shipment did not have a dangerous goods declaration nor could it be moved by water since it did not meet the requirements or 49CFR176.905.  The customer responded and had the fuel tank completely removed and the fuel drained from the regulator and fuel lines and shipped the cargo, as it was originally billed in a non hazardous status.
column169: The customer was not completely familiar with the hazardous nature of the forklift and he was not aware that his warehouse had loaded thee unit in the container.  There need to be better communications between the party loading the container and those prepairing the shipping papers.
column172: Container, no description given (do not use if at all possible)

column168: The customer was advised about tthe need to declare the vehicle as hazardous but failed to provide proper documentation prior to the receipt of the cargo by the ocean carrier.  The document that was received still left doubt as to wheter the vehicle was hazardous or not even though the customer signed a document indicating that the battery was disconnected and that the fuel was drained to 1/4 tank or less.  We notified the customer of the problems with their documentation.
column169: The customer need training on the shipping requirements of vehicles over water in the domestic trade lane.  She need to be trained on 49CFR173.220 and 176.905 specifically.

column62: Human Error; Missing Component or Device
column168: The forward top washout cap came off during transit. The driver didn’t know when it came off. As the driver applied his brakes for the redlight at the intersection of SH-44 @ Adkinson Ave he savv the product come out of the 3 inch washout port and then pulled over on the service road and stopped. The product splashed out onto the highway and the dripped off the side of the trailer onto the service road. Once the truck stopped, no more product was released from the washout port. The fire department estimated 15-20 gallons of product was spilled onto the highway. one lane of the highway was closed to keep traffic out of the product.  Service Transport Cc). in-house clean up crew neutralized the product with lime and swept it up off the pavement. It was placed in a 55 gallon drum and taked back to our terminal where it will be disposed of properly.
column169: Retrain both drivers and wash rack personnel on the importance of checking all openings prior to leaving the terminal for loading. Get with the shipper and loading facility to double check caps and dome lids after they complete loading.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: THE DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE SITE AND WENT INTO THE OFFICE TO GET THE ATG READINGS (ATG AUTOMATIC TANK GUAGE) HE THEN CAME OUT DROPPED 1800 GALLONS OF SUPER AND 1200 GALLONS OF SPECIAL. WHEN THE SPECIAL WAS FINSHED THE DRIVER HOOKED HIS HOSE TO THE 1ST OF 2 REGULAR COMPARTMENTS ON THE TRAILER. (COMP #4 A 1000 GAL #5= 1500 GALS) HE THEN HOOKED INTO THE 2ND OF 2 FINSHED DROPPING AND WENT BACK INTO THE STATION GOT THE FINISHED ATG READING AND WENT TO THE 2ND PART OF THE SPLIT UNAWARE OF THE SPILL UNDERGROUND. WHEN THE DRIVER GOT TO HIS NEXT STOP HE RECEIVED A CALL FROM XOM LEAD MAN INQUIRING ABOUT THE DELIVERY. THE DRIVER SAID THAT EVERYTHING WENT FINE. AFTER PRODUCT WAS BEING SAFELY PUMPED INTO CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANK, HE WENT TO THE SIDE BOX ON THE TRUCK AND RETRIEVED A WRENCH IN ORDER TO OPEN THE 3RD COMPARTMENT WHICH HANDLE WAS BROKEN. AFTER THE 4TH COMPARTMENT WAS SUCCESSFULLY UNLOADED HE SWITCHED THE HOSE TO THE 3RD COMPARTMENT AND WAS ABLE TO OPEN THE VALVE WITH THE WRENCH, AND HE SUCCESSFULLY UNLOADED THAT COMPARTMENT. WHEN COMPARTMENT WAS EMPTY HE WENT TO CLOSE THE VALVE, BUT HAD TO GO BACK TO THE SIDE TOOL BOX AND RETRIEVE ANOTHER WRENCH IN ORDER TO CLOSE THE VALVE. ONCE AT THE TOOL BOX HE HEARD A SWOOSH SOUND FROM THE VENT PIPE ON THE CUSTOMERS STORAGE TANK. HE LOOKED UP AND SAW PRODUCT SPEWING OUT OF THE PIPE IN WHICH STICK READING ARE TAKEN ON THE EAST SIDE OF THE TANK. HE SAID THAT IT CAME OUT IN 3 QUICK BURSTS BEFORE HE WAS ABLE TO SUCCESSFULLY STOP THE FLOW OF AIR BY HITTING THE EMERGENCY CUT OFF VALVE. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE TANK WAS OVERFILLED AND ACCORDING TO TANK CHARTS PROVIDED BY MANAGER OF STORAGE TANK ABOUT 10 GALLONS OR LESS WAS DISCHARGED FROM SITE STORAGE TANK.
column169: OWNER OF TANK SHOULD NOT ORDER FUEL THAT WOULD ALLOW TANK TO BE FILLED TO MORE THAN 90% OF CAPACITY. AN OVERFILL ALARM SHOULD BE INSTALLED IN ORDER TO PREVENT FILLING TANK TO MORE THAN SUGGESTED CAPACITY. DRIVER DELIVERING FUEL TO TANK SHOULD HAVE ACCESS TO ACCURATE COPY OF TANK STRAPPING CHART, AND SHOULD TAKE READINGS BEFORE UNLOADING IN ORDER TO INSURE TANK HAS CAPACITY FOR PRODUCT TO FIT WITHOUT FILLING TO MORE THAN 90% OF CAPACITY.

column169: DISCUSSED WITH THE SHIPPER ON THE IMPORTANCE OF MAKING SURE PACKAGING OF PAILS, DRUMS TOTES OR MISCELLANEOUS CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, CHEMICALS AND LIQUID MUST BE SAFE FOR TRANSPORTING AND TRAVELING. THE SEAMS ON THE PACKAGING MUST BE ABLE TO HOLD LIQUID WITHOUT LEAKING OUT. THE DURABILITY OF A DRUM, PAIL, BAGS AND, OR TOTE MUST BE ABLE TO MAINTAIN THE LIQUIDS OR POWERS TO PREVENT PACKAGE DETERIORATION. IMPORTANT THAT LIDS AND TOPS OF PACKAGES ARE SECURED AND TIGHTENED BEFORE ALLOWING TO MOVE. TOTES AND DRUMS WITH VALVES MUST BE SAFELY CLOSED AND THE CONTAINER, PACKAGING, MUST BE DURABLE TO ENSURE NO LIQUID OR POWDER IS ALLOWED TO BE RELEASED. DISCUSS WITH SHIPPER ON PROPER, SAFE AND RELIABLE PACKAGING TO PREVENT EASY RELEASE OF PRODUCT. PACKAGING OF CHEMICALS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND LIQUIDS MUST BE THOROUGHLY INSPECTED BEFORE IT LEAVES ORIGIN!

column169: DISCUSS WITH THE SHIPPER ON THE IMPORTANCE OF MAKING SURE PACKAGING OF PAILS, DRUMS, TOTES OR MISCELLANEOUS CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, CHEMICALS AND LIQUID MUST BE SAFE FOR TRANSPORTING AND TRAVELING. THE SEAMS CNTHE PACKAGING MUST BE ABLE TO HOLD LIQUID WITHOUT LEAKING OUT. THE DURABILITY OF A DRUM, PAIL, BAGS AND, OR TOTE MUST BE ABLE MAINTAIN THE LIQUIDS OR POWDERS TO PREVENT PACKAGE DETERIORATION. IMPORTANT THAT LIDS ANDTOPS OF PACKAGES ARE SECURED AND TIGHTENED BEFORE ALLOWING TO MOVE. TOTES AND DRUMS WITH VALVES MUST BE SAFELY CLOSED AND THE CONTAINER, PACKAGING, MUST BE DURABLE TO ENSURE NO LIQUID OR POWDER IS ALLOWED TO BE RELEASED DISCUSS WITH SHIPPER ON PROPER, SAFE AND RELIABLE PACKAGING TO PREVENT EASY RELEASE OF PRODUCT. PACKAGING OF CHEMICALS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND LIQUIDS MUST BE THOROUGHLY INSPECTED BEFORE IT LEAVES ORIGIN!

column168: Acid was loaded in a closed 28 ft trailer tractor combination. Dunnage was not used around the acid to protect from freight shifting in transit. Another piece of freightwas loaded above and in front of the acid which fell on top of the acid in transit crushing one of the glass containers containing the acid. The acid shipment was on therear of the trailer and was immediately found when the door of the trailer was opened. Employee notified supervisor on duty (Laurence McGillvray) at that time and Iimediately notified all employees to the situation and advised to stay away from spill area untill further notice. I gathered all information needed and called chemtrecfor proper instructions. After calling Chemtrec I than notified Conway safety Supervisor Jeff Turner and informed him of our situation and disscussed safetyprecautions and clean up options as noted in safety response guide and decided the only option was to soak up spill with floor dry and call out hazard clean upcompany to take care of the clean up. I checked the trailer to make sure that it was safe to do so and spread floor dry on the spilled product and shut the trailer dooorand applied a lock to keep the trailer from being opened and moved the trailer to a safe area to wait for clean up. Made sure at this time everybody knew what thesituation was and that there was nothig leaking from the trailer and waited for clean up crew. Clean up crew responded and cleaned up the spill with no further complications.
column169: Reinforced Conways loading policies with the loader and stressed if he had followed training procedures these incidents could be elimated.

The freight came in on a FedEx Feeder Aircraft. It was FedEx flight #7652, #7653 or#7670. While the spill was contained to the outer box, there was a very strong odorassociated with the spill. The box was opened to reveal hidden packaging discrepancies. They were: No positive closure & insufficient absorbant material. Asa result of the spill, FedEx Flight 1300 took a 33 minute delay. The FAA was notified, I left a message for LAX FAA personnel as directed by the 24 hour Communications Center Duty Officer. The freight was subsequently in spected by SAGonzalez, ONT FAA FSDO.

column169: RETRAINING ON SAFE USE AND OPERATION OF THE FORKLIFT. WHEN ENTERING TRAILERS WITH PAILS, DRUMS OR TOTES LOADED AND HIDDEN BEHIND FREIGHT, WHEN USING BLADES, ENTER WITH CAUTION TO AVOID PUNCTURING PAILS. FREIGHT PLACED ON DOCK MUST BE SECURED AND PROPERLY BLOCKED AND SHROUDED TO AVOID EASY PUNCTURING FROM OTHER FREIGHT OR FORKLIFT. DISCUSS DURING PRESHIFT ON SAFETY OF DOCKING, REMOVING AND TRANSFERRING CHEMICAL, LIQUID AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. BEWARE OF SURROUNDINGS WHEN WORKING ON THE DOCK AND WHILE TRANSFERRING PACKAGES OF CHEMICALS, LIQUIDS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. PAILS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS, AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE. MTY PALLETS AND PLYWOOD TO PREVENT DAMAGED OR PUNCTURING. LEAVE PAIL OF HAZARDOUS OR CHEMICAL IN THE BAY UNTIL TRAILER IS READY FOR CLOSE. EVEN COACHING ON LOADING/DOCK AWARENESS.

BEING AWARE OF SURROUNDINGS WHEN WORKING ON THE DOCK AND WHILE TRANSFERRING PACKAGES OF CHEMICALS, LIQUIDS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. PAILS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, MTY PALLETS AND PLYWOOD TO PREVENT EASY DAMAGED AND PUNCTURING.

column168: Augustine ortiz came to me, after discovering that a 300 gallon tote of class 8 phosphoric acid was leaking out of a release valve. I, Russ Simons, examined the tote and found no visible damage to the tote but noticed that the valve would drip every minute or so. We placed the tote in a trailer by its self with absorbant to catch the drippings. I could not find any other damage to the tote. After examining the tote, I called Mike Sorensen, the safety manager, he instructed me to call the shipper's emergency contact number for further assistance. Delaval was contacted and made aware of the spill and they suggested a hazmat team come in and transfer the contents to another tote. At this point i turned the handling of this over to Katie powell the OS&D Clerk who handles these issues.
column169: My recommendation to prevent this spill from reoccurring would be to have the valves which are made of plastic, be inspected, even/time the corrosive contents that it carries are dispensed, to make sure that the valves seals and mechanics are not compromised by the corrosive liquid.

column168: UNIVAR DRIVER WAS MAKING HIS DAILY DELIVERIES AND ON HIS NEXT TO LAST STOP HE NOTICED A SMALL WET SPOT NEAR A SULFURIC ACID TOTE WHICH WAS THE LAST THING ON HIS TRAILER, HE PUT AN ABSORBENT PAD DOWN TO WIPE IT UP AND THROUGHT EVERYTHING WAS OK, HE WAS HEADED TO HIS LAST STOP AND CALLED IN TO REPORT THE SPILL ON THE TRAILER FLOOR, I ASKED HIM HOW BAD IT WAS LEAKING, AND HE SAID JUST A SMALL AMOUNT WITH NOTHING DRIPPING OUT OF THE TRAILER. I INSTRUCTED HIM TO GET TO A SAFE PLACE TO PULL OVER AND RECHECK AND CALL ME BACK. HE PULLED IN TO A SMALL TRUCK STOP AWAY FROM EVERYTHING AND RECHECKED HIS LOAD, HE CALLED ME BACK AND SAID THAT THE TOTE WAS STILL LEAKING BUT NOTHING WAS DRIPPING ON THE GROUND, HE PLACED MORE SPILL CONTAINMENT PADS AROUND THE TOTE. I INSTRUCTED HIM TO STAY THERE AND WE WOULD GET SOMEONE THERE TO TRANSFER THE TOTE AND TAKE CARE OF IT. I CONTACTED NUWAY INDUSTRIAL SERVICES AND THEY ARE TRANSFERING THE MATERIAL INTO DRUMS. AS STATED NOTHING LEAKED THROUGH TO THE GROUND AND IT IS ESTIMATED THAT AROUND 15 LBS OF MATERIAL LEAKED OUT OF THE TOTE. THE DRIVER SAID THAT THE TOTE APPEARED TO BE LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM SOMEWHERE BUT IT WAS DRY AT THE VALVE AREA AND WAS DRY AROUND ALL OF THE TOP OPENINGS AND ALL OUTLETS WERE TIGHT.

column168: UNIVAR SPARTANBURG DRIVER HAD JUST LEFT THE WAREHOUSE HEADED TO HIS FIRST STOP, HE WAS ABOUT 6 MILES FROM THE WAREHOUSE WHEN THE TURBOCHARGER WENT OUT ON HIS TRUCK, HE CONTACTED THE TRUCK SHOP ABOUT THE TURBOCHARGER, THEY TOLD HIM TO CHECK FOR ANY OUTSIDE DAMAGE TO THE TURBO AND IF NONE TO TRY AND EASE THE TRUCK BACK TO THE WAREHOUSE. HE PULLED OVER TO SEE WHAT HAD HAPPENED TO THE TURBOCHARGER AND AS HE GOT OUT OF HIS TRUCK HE NOTICED AN ORDOR COMING FROM HIS TRAILER. HE OPENED THE TRAILER DOOR AND NOTICED A WET SPOT IN THE TRAILER FLOOR BUT COULD NOT GET TO THE DRUMS DUE TO THE WAY THEY WERE LOADED BUT KNEW THE PRODUCT WAS ACRYLIC ACID GLACIAL DUE TO THE ORDOR. THE LEAK WAS MINIMAL SO HE STARTED BACK TO THE WAREHOUSE. HE THEN CALLED THE WAREHOUSE TO LET US KNOW WHAT WAS GOING ON, AT THE TIME I TALKED TO TIM HE WAS ONLY ABOUT 10 MINUTES AWAY, WHEN HE ARRIVED BACK AT THE WAREHOUSE THE TRAILER WAS UNLOADED AND THE LEAKING DRUM WAS FOUND, IT WAS A FACTORY PACKED DRUM STILL SHRINK WRAPPED ON THE PALLET THAT IT CAME FROM THE MFG. ON. THE LEAK WAS CAUSED BY A PROTRUDING NAIL IN THE PALLET THAT RUBBED A SMALL HOLE IN THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM. THE DRUM WAS PLACED INTO AN OVERPACK DRUM, THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT PADS AND PLACED IN THE OVERPACK DRUM. THE TRAILER WAS THEN MOPPED OUT WITH A DEODORIZING AGENT. THE LEAKING DRUM WAS WEIGHED AND IT WAS DETERMINED THAT APPROX. 30 LBS OF MATERIAL WAS LOST OUT OF THE DRUM BUT WAS RECOVERED IN THE CLEAN UP OR ABSORBED INTO THE TRAILER FLOOR.
column169: INSPECT PALLETS FOR LOOSE OR PROTRUDING NAILS PRIOR TO SHIPMENT.

column168: Emily Friend, Corridor Manager, reported eastbound Train MROGR 27, Lead Locomotive UP 8468, observed Ammonium Nitrate white powder pouring from the side of Hoppercar MP718091 parked on the sideing at Devils Slide Siding at Mile Post 960.0 of the Evanston Subdivision in Morgan, UT. Leon Hendrickson, Manager of Hazardous Materials, was notified and responded. All required State and Federal notifications were completed. Hendrickson advised Pacific West, Contractor, was en route to assist. He later advised approximately 2000 pounds of product was released from the hopper car and the leak was stopped. column168: Original shipment consisted of 64 five gallon crimp on lid steel pails, palletized 16 pails to a pallet. The pallets were loaded on a 28 ft trailer tractor combination. The pallets were all floor loaded but the handler did not use any dunnage to protect the shipment from moving in transit and one of the pallets shifted against the wall allowing one of the pails to rub against a rib on the wall of the trailer crushing the lid enough to allow the contents to seep out during transit. Employee upon finding the spill notified Larry McGillvray, the supervisior on shift, at which time I removed all employees fron the immediate area of the spill and retrieved all the appropriate paper work needed to report the spill and called Chemtrec to receive the proper procedure for cleanup and disposition of the material involved. The spilled material was soaked up with floor dry and the damaged container and the contaminated floor dry was put in a salvage container for proper disposal.
column169: Procedures and training are allready in place at Conway terminals but it must be stressed to all employees to take every precaution in every situation and use properloading procedures to keep freight from damage in transit.

Mr. Bavier stated the product was released onto the top and sides the tankcar from a loose liquid eduction valve. Mr. Baylor confirmed there was no ground or water contamination. Mr. Bavie’ advised the product solidified and the release was stopped.

Paul Gonzalez, Gate Clerk, reported container CSXU 985309, had released product while located in Row D, Space 742, City ofIndustry, CA. Mr. Gonzalez stated the product was releasing from the underside of the container and confirmed there were no waterways affected. Dean Cooper, Manager, Hazardous Materials, was notified and advised he would have Transloading Environmental enroute to investigate. While off loading the non hazardous drums, located one drum identified as Stepanquat 65NF, with Corrosive andFlammable markings, that was leaking. The drum was positioned against the left sidewall, three rows from the nose. The poly drumhad been crushed from adjacent drums shifting Into it during transit. A two inch crack on the bottom radius of the drum was the sourceof the leak. There was no floor damage to cause the crack in the drum, which indicates the drum may have been dropped duringloading. Estimated 30 gallons of product was lost during transit. The damaged drum was patched and placed into a salvage drum forsecurement. The other three hazardous drums were eventually located and found to be intact. The residue was cleaned from theflooring, and the drums, along with the salvage drum, were placed back into the on'ginal container. The container was then released formovement onto the consignee.•i••• • -

column168: Dean Cooper, Manager, Hazardous Materials, reported tank car ACFX 77511 released an unknown amount of product within railyard limits, Bakersfield, CA. Manager Cooper advised the release was discovered during the switching of an interchange cut, and the tank car had been moved to the RIP track, where it can be isolated. Manager Cooper further advised ACTI, the railroad’s hazmat contractor, would be dispatched to investigate. At 06:O8PM, Manager Cooper advised the ACTI contractor reported approximately seven gallons of material had sprayed across the top of the tankcar, and the release appeared to be from the manway. Manager Cooper advised the material did not reach the ground. He further advised repairs and car cleaning would occur on 06/29/07 during daylight hours. Inspection found one of the eight manway swing bolts loose on the forward edge of the manway. The manway gasket was distorted and pushed out at the loose bolt, apparently caused by product liquid surge during switching operations. The inverted ‘J’ type manway gasket was so distorted it could not be reused. A temporary gasket was made with Gore-Tex 1/2 inch joint sealant to secure the manway. ACTI cleaned the residue from the surface of the car, and it was relapsed for movement onto the consignee.

column169: RETRAINING ON SAFE USE AND OPERATION OF THE FORKLIFT. WHEN ENTERING TRAILERS WITH PAILS, DRUMS OR TOTESLOADED AND HIDDEN BEHIND FREIGHT,WHEN USING BLADES, ENTER WITH CAUTION TO AVOID PUNCTURING PAILS. FREIGHTPLACED ON DOCK MUST BE SECURED AND PROPERLY BLOCKED AND SHROUDED TO AVOID EASY PUNCTURING FROM OTHER FREK iHTOR FORKLIFT. DISCUSS DURING PRESHIFT ON THE SAFETY OF DOCKING, REMOVING AND TRANSFERRING CHEMICAL, LIQUID ANDHAZARDOUS MATERIALS. BEING AWARE OF SURROUNDINGS WHEN WORKING. ON THE DOCK AND WHILE TRANSFERRING PACKAGE 5 OFCHEMICALS, LIQUIDS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS! PAILS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BECOMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, MTY PALLETS AND PLYWOOD TO PREVENT EASY DAMAGED AND PUNCTURING.
