column168: The material was loaded at the shippers whse., where while in the process the super sacks were damage in the loading process.The damage was limited to two small holes int he sides about mid way on the sacks.It appears that the bottom of another pallet made contact with the leaking sacks causing them to tear. The driver was not allowed in the loading area, and did not see the damage when loaded.The truck was stopped in a roadside DOT inspection in Pennsylvania. The inspector checked the load and discovered the release which was contained to the trailer. The spill was no more than about 10 ounces.There also appeared to be a sack that the powder sifted through the sacks.Regional Integrated Logistics was notified by the driver immediately. Regional notified WEGO chemical and inquired as to how they wanted to proceed. WEGO said to call CHEMTREC, which was done. CHEMTREC supplied the name of MINUTEMAN spill response which was called to do the cleanup.The release occured over the distance of approx. 100 miles and 2 hours.
column169: Our drivers are now required to inspect the loads before they close doors and proceed on the trip. They are to reject any packaging that they feel is not adequate.Shippers in our opinion should be held more accountable in these instances.

column168: IN ORDER TO AVERT A COLLISION WITH ANOTHER VEHICLE THE DRIVER OF THE NOONAN ENERGY CARGO TANKER WAS FORCED TO TAKE EVASIVE MEASURES.  THE RESULTS OF THIS ACTIONS PREVENTED AN ACCIDENT THAT COULD HAVE RESULTED IN SEVERE PERSONAL INJURIES TO BOTH HE AND THE OCCUPANT OF THE OTHER VEHICLE AS WELL AS, PROPERTY DAMAGE TO A NEARBY BUILDING.  THE CARGO TANKER TAKER TIPPED ON TO ITS SIDE RESULTING IN A PUNCTURE TO THE TANKERS SHELL.  THE PUNCTURE HOLE WAS A FEW INCHES IN DIAMETER ABOUT HALF WAY UP THE TANKER'S SHELL.  NOONAN ENERGY PERSONAL, THE SPRINGFIELD FIRE DEPARTMENT AND SPRINGFIELD POLICE AND MASSACHUSETTS STATE POLICE TRUCK UNIT RESPONDED IMMEDIATELY.  CLEAN-UP CREWS FROM BOTH NOONAN ENERGY AND THE SPRINGFIELD FIRE DEPARTMENT PREVENTED THE MIGRATION OF OIL AND DEPLOYED BOOMS AND ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THE MASSACHUSETTS DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION WAS NOTIFIED WHEN NOONAN PERSONNEL ARRIVED ON THE SCENE.  WESTERN MASSACHUSETTS ENVIRONMENTAL CO. WAS CALLED IN TO DO THE PROFESSIONAL CLEAN-UP AND HYDRO-ENVIRONMENTAL TECHNOLOGIES, INC. WAS HIRED TO PERFORM THE REQUIRED LSP DUTIES.  THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WAS NOTIFIED WITHIN 2 1/2 HOURS AFTER THE INCIDENT.  THE VEHICLE WAS OFF-LOADED ON TO ANOTHER CARGO TANKER.  THE NUMBER OF GALLONS INVOLVED CAN ONLY BE ESTIMATED BECAUSE WE CANNOT BE EXACT AS TO HOW MANY GALLONS WERE ON THE TRUCK AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT.  WE DO KNOW THE VEHICLES CAPACITY, 2800 GALLONS AND THAT NO DELIVERIES HAD BEEN MADE.  WE DO KNOW THAT 1960 GALLONS WE PUMPED-OFF TO ANOTHER TRUCK.  WESTERN MASS ENVIRONMENTAL'S VACUUM TRUCK REMOVED 225 GALLONS FROM THE STREET AND APPROXIMATELY 550 GALLONS WERE PUMPED FROM THE STREET ON TO ANOTHER TANK TRUCK.  THE REMAINING OIL WAS PICKED-UP BY VARIOUS ABSORBENTS AND PLACED IN DRUMS.  THE CLEAN-UP WAS COMPLETED IN APPROXIMATELY 3 1/2 HOURS.  THE SPRINGFIELD POLICE DEPARTMENT FOUND NO VIOLATIONS BY THE NOONAN ENERGY DRIVER AND THE MASSACHUSETTS STATE POLICE TRUCK UNIT INSPECTED THE VEHICLE ON SITE AND FOUND NO VEHICLE SAFETY VIOLATIONS.
column169: WITH THE ASSISTANCE OF OUR INSURANCE COMPANY, NOONAN ENERGY HAS INCREASED THE SCOPE OF ITS ANNUAL "DRIVER SAFETY CLASS" TO EMPHASIS DRIVER AWARENESS AND DEFENSIVENESS.  DRIVER SAFETY IS TALKED ABOUT THROOUGHOUT THE YEAR, MAKING IT A MAJOR CONCERN OF ALL OUR EMPLOYEES.  AS A RESULTS, NOONAN ENERGY HAS OFTEN CREDITED BY ITS INSURER FOR THE OUTSTANDING DRIVING RECORD OUR EMPLOYEES HAVE PRODUCED.

column168: Driver traveling East on US HWY 84, when he was told that the rear trailer tandem was smoking. Rear air valve on rear trailer was not closed properly as needed, which resulted in the brakes locking and catching on fire. This resulted in the rear of the trailer catching on fire. The shipment in question was loaded on the rear of the trailer and involved with the fire and cleanup. Outside assistance was called for proper cleanup and disposal. This was Environmental Hazmat Services, Inc., Dothan, AL. Amount of actual release of the hazardous materials is unknown, if any. Because of the fire, anything located on the rear of the trailer was basically destroyed. This material was disposed of properly following all regulatory guidelines.
column169: Training was done to emphasize the importance of a vehicle inspection to make sure all connections, including air, are made properly. This will help to eliminate future problems, that could have the same result. Any valves at the rear of a set of pups should always be checked before moving the vehicle.
